@page "/privacy"
@inject SiteConfig Site

<PageTitle>Privacy Notice — @Site.SiteTitle</PageTitle>
<HeadContent>
    <meta name="description" content="Privacy notice for @Site.SiteTitle" />
</HeadContent>

<section class="section page-head">
    <div class="container">
        <p class="eyebrow">Privacy Notice</p>
        <h1>What this site knows about you</h1>
        <p class="muted">The complete list — it's short. No ads, no analytics trackers, no data sales. Ever.</p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="legal">
    <div class="container prose">
        <h2>If you just browse</h2>
        <p>
            Nothing is collected about you. There are no third-party trackers, ad networks, or
            analytics scripts on this site. Your theme choice (dark/light) is stored in your own
            browser's localStorage and never leaves your device.
        </p>

        <h2>If you sign in</h2>
        <p>
            Sign-in uses a provider you already trust (GitHub, Google, or Discord). This site
            receives and stores only your <strong>email address</strong> and <strong>display
            name</strong> from that provider — never a password. Your email is used to identify
            your account across providers and is not shown publicly or shared with anyone.
        </p>
        <p>
            If you set a custom display name or upload an avatar, those are stored too. Avatars
            are resized on the server and stripped of embedded photo metadata (EXIF) before being
            saved.
        </p>

        <h2>If you comment</h2>
        <p>
            Your comment text, the time you posted it, and your account are stored so the comment
            can be displayed and so you can delete it later.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>About anonymous comments</strong>: choosing "post anonymously" hides your name
            and avatar from other visitors, but the comment remains linked to your account in the
            database — the site owner can see who wrote it. This exists so moderation works;
            it is not a promise of anonymity from the site owner.
        </p>

        <h2>If you use the contact form</h2>
        <p>
            The name, email address, subject, and message you submit are stored in the site's
            database and also delivered to @Site.OwnerName by email. They're used solely to read
            and reply to your message.
        </p>

        <h2>Cookies</h2>
        <p>
            One kind: a sign-in session cookie, set only after you sign in, so the site remembers
            who you are. No tracking or advertising cookies exist here.
        </p>

        <h2>Where data lives &amp; how long</h2>
        <p>
            Everything is stored on infrastructure operated by the site owner — no third-party
            data processors beyond your chosen sign-in provider and the email delivery of contact
            messages. Data is kept until you delete it or ask for it to be deleted.
        </p>

        <h2>Your choices</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Delete any of your own comments directly on the page they appear.</li>
            <li>Remove your avatar or display name on your profile page.</li>
            <li>
                Ask for your account and everything tied to it to be deleted by emailing
                <a href="mailto:@Site.ContactEmail">@Site.ContactEmail</a> — this is honored
                without fuss.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <p class="muted">
            This notice is written in good faith by @Site.OwnerName and reflects exactly how the
            software behaves. It is not legal advice.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>
